<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: FESTIVAL NEWS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH KLEID, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Mural Won't Make Festival: The restoration of David Alfaro Siqueiros' "Tropical 
America" mural in Olvera Street -- which is being billed as "an image for the 
entire Los Angeles Festival" -- will not take place until long after the 
September arts festival, according to the Friends of Mexico, which is actually 
undertaking the project with the J. Paul Getty Museum. Spokeswoman Miriam 
Bertram said that the city's uncertainty surrounding future plans for Olvera 
Street has delayed work on the mural which was commissioned in 1932, but 
covered with a coat of white paint two years later because it was seen by many 
as Communist propaganda. Bertram said that "end painting" on the mural -- which 
depicted a crucified Mexican with a huge eagle perched above him on the cross 
-- is now scheduled for January, 1991. BETH KLEID 
</P>
</TEXT>
