<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: STOLEN CAR TRACKING SYSTEM GOES ON LINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An anti-theft system that uses radio signals to lead police to stolen cars went 
on line Tuesday in Los Angeles County. 
</P>
<P>
The Stolen Vehicle Recovery Network's key component is a homing device, 
manufactured by the Massachusetts-based electronics firm LoJack. 
</P>
<P>
The system costs about $595 for a private citizen to install. When a 
LoJack-equipped car is reported stolen, police enter the report into the 
state's stolen vehicle system computer, which sends a radio signal from one of 
seven transmission towers throughout the county. 
</P>
<P>
All but two police departments -- Culver City and Long Beach -- have joined the 
47-agency recovery network. 
</P>
<P>
The California Highway Patrol is coordinating the three-year pilot program, 
which was unveiled at a news conference attended by county Sheriff's Department 
and Los Angeles police officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Receiver on dashboard of police vehicles tracks locations of stolen 
cars. JAVIER MENDOZA / For The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
