<HEADLINE>
<P>
KENJIRO TAKAYANAGI; JAPANESE TELEVISION PIONEER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kenjiro Takayanagi, 91, considered the father of Japanese television. An 
electrical engineer, Takayanagi achieved the first television transmission in 
Japan in 1926 and developed the main component of a television camera in 1933 
only months after Vladimir K. Zworykin did so in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
After teaching at a Japanese college, he worked for Japan Broadcasting Co. 
(NHK) and then at Victor Co. of Japan, where he later became vice president. On 
Monday in Yokosuka, Japan. 
</P>
