<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: MAN ARRAIGNED IN BREAK-IN AT REAGAN'S 
ESTATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A man authorities accused of climbing a fence and entering former President 
Ronald Reagan's Bel-Air estate on July 4 has pleaded not guilty in federal 
court to charges of threatening Reagan's life. 
</P>
<P>
Gregory Stuart Gordon, 32, is charged with one count of threatening the life of 
an ex-President and faces a maximum of three years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
Gordon was ordered Monday to stand trial Sept. 11 before U.S. District Judge 
Edward Rafeedie, and is being held without bail, according to spokeswoman Grace 
Denton of the U.S. attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
Federal authorities said Reagan and his wife, Nancy, were at their home when 
Gordon scaled a fence and headed for the front door. He was stopped by a Secret 
Service agent before he reached the doorway where Nancy Reagan was standing, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
