<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. NEIL SOLOMON: HEART MEDICATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: My father is taking nitroglycerin for angina. I know that it's been 
around a long time. 
</P>
<P>
Isn't there anything newer and better? New drugs are being developed every day. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Medication must be determined by the patient's own physician. I have no 
basis for saying that one medication is better than another for a patient I 
have never seen. 
</P>
<P>
Having said that, I should add that nitroglycerin is a preferred medication for 
many patients with stable angina pectoris. A patient can take it after symptoms 
develop, or as a preventive. Moreover, side effects associated with 
nitroglycerin, for the most part, are acceptable. Another advantage is that the 
drug is inexpensive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
